  "text": "The importance of both microtubules and cellulose in determining the direction of cell expansion has been clear for many years (reviewed in [CITATION_1] , Wasteneys & Yang 2004 , Lloyd & Chan 2004 . The observation that the cellulose deposition pattern normally mirrors the pattern of cortical microtubules in expanding cells led to formulation of the cortical microtubule/cellulose microfibril coalignment hypothesis, hereafter referred to as the co-alignment hypothesis, which states that movement of cellulose synthase enzyme complexes in the plasma membrane is constrained by interactions with the cortical microtubules (Giddings & Staehelin 1991) . The energy of cellulose polymerization supplies the force needed to move the enzyme complex through the membrane, and it only needs to be guided by direct or indirect interactions with the cortical microtubules.",
